    title: 'The Blue Jackal',
    body: `Chandarava was an ordinary jackal who always wished to be grander than he was. One evening, chasing a scrap of food, he tumbled into a washerman's great vat of blue dye. When he climbed out, his fur had turned a brilliant, shining blue — like no animal anyone had ever seen!\n\nAt first Chandarava was frightened. But when he walked into the forest, every animal stopped and stared. The lions, tigers, and elephants had never seen such a strange blue creature. "Surely this is a magical king sent to rule us!" they whispered.\n\nChandarava saw his chance. "Yes," he announced grandly, "I have been sent to be your king!" The animals bowed. They brought him the finest food and fanned him with leaves. He lived in great comfort, with lions as guards and deer as servants. But he had to guard one secret: no one must ever learn he was just a common jackal.\n\nOne bright full-moon night, a pack of jackals in the distance began to howl their evening song — Hoooowl! Hooowl! Chandarava's heart leapt. The sound pulled at him so strongly that, without thinking, he lifted his head and howled too — a plain, ordinary jackal's howl!\n\nThe animals froze. "A jackal's cry! Our great blue king is no king at all — only a jackal in fancy colours!" His secret was out. Red-faced under all that blue, Chandarava scampered away into the night. And as he ran, he understood: no clever disguise can hide who you truly are for long. It is far easier — and far happier — to simply be yourself.`,
    moral: 'No disguise can hide who you really are; it is best to be yourself.',
