    body: `A kind brahmin was walking home through the forest when he passed an old iron cage. Inside paced a tiger. "Oh, good sir!" cried the tiger. "I am so thirsty and trapped. Please open the door and let me drink at the river. I promise to do you no harm."\n\nThe brahmin's heart was soft, and against his better sense, he lifted the latch. The moment the door swung open, the tiger stretched and grinned. "How lucky! I have been hungry for days, and here you are." "But you promised!" gasped the brahmin. "Promises made in a cage do not count," laughed the tiger.\n\nThe brahmin trembled. "Let us ask three others whether this is fair," he begged. The tiger agreed. They asked a tree and a buffalo, but both had been treated unkindly by people, and neither took the brahmin's side.\n\nAt last they met a clever jackal. "I am confused," said the jackal, scratching his ear. "Please show me exactly how this happened. The brahmin was in the cage?" "No, no!" growled the tiger. "I was in the cage!" "This cage? You are far too big to fit." "I am not! Watch!" And the tiger sprang into the cage to prove it.\n\nQuick as a wink, the jackal flicked the latch shut. CLICK! "There," he said kindly to the brahmin. "Everything is now exactly as it was. Shall we leave this ungrateful fellow as we found him?" The brahmin thanked the clever jackal again and again, and walked home wiser — knowing that a kindness should always be met with kindness, never with a broken promise.`,
