    title: "The Bear's Warm Cave",
    body: `High in the hills lived a big brown bear named Bhalu, who kept a cozy cave and a store of berries for the long winter. One evening, dark clouds rolled in and a fierce storm began — rain lashing, wind howling, thunder rumbling far away. Bhalu settled into his warm, dry cave, glad to be safe inside.\n\nBut then he heard small, frightened sounds at the cave's mouth. A little fawn, shivering and soaked, had lost her way in the storm and could not find her herd. Behind her huddled a wet sparrow and a trembling rabbit, all blown off course by the wind.\n\nBhalu was big, the storm was scary, and the cave was his own. He could have growled them away. Instead, his great heart melted. "Come in, come in, little ones," he rumbled gently. "There is room for everyone." He spread dry leaves for them to rest on, shared his berries one by one, and told warm, funny stories until the frightened animals forgot to be afraid.\n\nAll night the storm raged outside, but inside the cave it was snug and full of friendship. By morning the sky was washed clear and bright blue. The fawn found her herd, the sparrow flew home, and the rabbit hopped off — but not before each one thanked the kind bear with all their heart.\n\nBhalu watched them go, his cave a little emptier but his heart very full. He had learned that a warm shelter shared in a storm is far cozier than one kept all to yourself.`,
